{"key":"processedPost-12451391","value":{"id":12451391,"first":12451292,"last":19671560,"when":1272166379,"utime":"04/25/10 06:32 AM","content":"If properly pasteurized coir contaminates before first flush, then it was your spawn, no doubt about it.&nbsp; I've left wet coir sitting around for months without mold, and my coir doormat is a few years old, and has never been infected with trich.&nbsp; The fact is, trich spores have a very hard time germinating on coir, so you need to look at your spawn and sterile technique.<br /><br />If you've ever tried to 'save' a contaminated project and let it puke spores all over your house, you're going to have a really hard time growing now due to the spore load.<br />RR","title":"Re: Trich problems in monotubs, anyone have a solution?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}